        <abstract> 
<p>Is extremely pleased by what FJP says of his book [<hi rend="italic">Origin</hi>]. Recalls how slowly he changed his own opinion; does not think anyone "could at once undergo so great a revolution in opinion". Thanks FJP for his intended notice of the work [<hi rend="italic">Bibl. Univers. Arch. Sci. Phys. &amp; Nat.</hi> 7 (1860)].</p>  
<p>Recommends an "excellent Review by that admirable Botanist Asa Gray" [<hi rend="italic">Am. J. Sci.</hi> 2d ser. 29 (1860): 153–84].</p> 
            <p>L. Agassiz is very bitter against CD’s book but H. G. Bronn, although very much opposed, "with noble liberality of sentiment" is going to superintend a German translation.</p>
            <p>As FJP’s studies lead him to reflect on "Geological Succession, Geographical Distribution, Classification, Homology &amp; Embryology", CD expects that he will go a little further with him because "these facts … are inexplicable on the theory of creation".</p>
        </abstract>
